psilo_primary_motives: My primary reasons are spiritual, for the purposes of experiencing awe and wonder and a heightening of meaning-making, religious ecstasy, things of this nature. Also as a professional artist, for artistic inspiration, and also at times as a social/shared experience with others. I used to view shrooms as a very solitary drug but increasingly find myself doing it mostly with other people, which might have more to do with when the opportunity naturally arises rather than as an intentional decision, though that change over the past decade feels significant to me.
psilo_additional_info: I have a history of psychosis which as I have grown has lessened significantly and now mostly arises in times of intense joy and excitement or intense fear and stress. In relation to this I could say psilocybin is a double-edged sword, when I was younger I certainly took unhealthy amounts of hallucinogens in response to my psychosis, though these days I feel that psilocybin allows me to integrate these parts of myself, good and bad, holistically.

psilo_primary_motives: I  use psilocybin to make colours brighter and music better. Trees and nature is more interesting on psilocybin. Which results in an interesting hike in nature. I find music really sounds good, particularly electronic dance music.  It helps dissociate at socially anxious social events like at a DJ show. I enjoy more being in a crowd or walking around an outdoor music festival. At smaller social events, a micro dose of psilocybin helps reduce the amount of alcohol consumed and saves money. A microdose makes one feel drunk and wobbly and makes the lazer lights and bright rave outfits really pop out and be interesting to look at. Some art displayed at outdoor music festivals really look fascinating while on psilocybin.
psilo_additional_info: I had a slowdown of psilocybin use in the past year but will try microdosing in the near future. I am leery about driving on a large psilocybin dose due to negative experiencies in the past. That was an issue with self dosing and I have learned from that experience. Within a month I will try a medium dose of 3.5 grams on one day of an upcoming music festival. I will try keep a journal of my experiences due to the fact it's been awhile since I did any psilocybin.

One of my psilocibin experiences brought back what I understand(and was able to verify some aspects with other involved persons) to be years of repressed memories, it was an extremely difficult time that required some therapy to work through how to support my sense of inner-child, redevelop a sense of security and new self with this integrated experience. I continued use after a gap and the therapy in a controlled manner and have since grown intellectually, emotionally, and spiritually, accepted myself and others around me for who they are and am greater able to remove myself from personal relationships that do not serve who I am and what I am working toward.

psilo_additional_info: A lot of these questions tell me you are asking a lot of wrong questions about how medicalized usage functions for people. Maybe that’s not the point, but a lot of these questions are WELL WEALTHY ABLED WELLNESS questions for elites that treat psilocybin as a cool new sweat lodge ayahausca fad. That is not how they are best used for people who actually need them to support their DISABLED WELLNESS. These two patterns are VERY distinct and the one your questions seem to prioritize are for the pattern of the former. The latter are the ones who need these studies to shift access, safety, and affordability to utilize psilocybin as a wellness tool in a complex regime of health management. I find this VERY concerning and not at all surprising. Hopefully you can divide this research into ACTUAL patients for whom this is a very useful tool, and the well wealthy and abled who use it as a way to go from already well and wealthy to more well and wealthier. I will not complete another survey for you if next year I find it is  again designed in a way that clearly deprioritizes patients for the privilege of the privileged.
